04346nam a2200661Ia 9781501727177DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20182004nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017271777 a10.7591/97815017271772doi  a(DE-B1597)515218  a(OCoLC)1076648772  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aJN8341.F58 2004 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a306.2/09462221 aFishman, Robert M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocracy's Voices :bSocial Ties and the Quality of Public Life in Spain /cRobert M. Fishman. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b8 tables, 25 charts/graphs, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Quality of Democracy -- t2. Exploring Social Ties -- t3. Social Ties and Discursive Horizons -- t4. Social Capital or Social Ties? -- t5. Pursuing Alternative Explanations -- t6. The Specific and the General for the Social Scientist -- t7. Beyond These Towns and Valleys -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBuilding on one of sociology's core ideas—that social ties can shape collective outcomes—Democracy's Voices shows that connections across class boundaries can remake public rhetoric and thus the quality of democratic life. Robert M. Fishman takes up a question of enduring significance to people concerned with the quality of democratic public life, focusing on why political rhetoric proves engaging and broadly relevant, or disengaging and narrow. The answer to that question, he argues, is to be found not only in the deeds of prominent politicians and the nature of official institutions but also in the existence and the character of social connections among ordinary citizens. Fishman's book, based on long-term fieldwork and systematic survey research in Spain, identifies the special contribution to democratic quality made by conversations between intellectuals and workers. Fishman focuses on what he calls the "discursive horizons" of local leaders and communities: the actual location of the problems and proposed remedies articulated in political rhetorics. Democracy's Voices shows how the subcultural context of social ties may accentuate or diminish their power to reshape rhetorics. Fishman argues that conversations are able to remake public rhetorics whereas ties that take the form of brokerage lack that ability. The book also offers a general critique of social capital theory and argues that the full ability of social ties to shape collective outcomes can only be observed when one distinguishes in useful ways among types of ties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDemocracyzSpain. 0aIntellectualszSpain. 0aLabor leaderszSpain. 0aPolitical participationzSpain. 4aEurope. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172717740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501727177423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501727177/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles